1. Round Robin Algorithm

Requests are distributed one by one in circular order.

Example:

Request 1 → Server A
Request 2 → Server B
Request 3 → Server C
Request 4 → Server A

Advantages
Simple
Easy to implement

Disadvantages
Does not check server load
Real-Time Example

Used in small websites where all servers have same capacity.

2. Weighted Round Robin

Servers with higher capacity get more requests.

Example:

Server A weight = 3
Server B weight = 1

Traffic:
A → A → A → B

Advantages

Better than normal Round Robin
Handles powerful servers efficiently
Real-Time Example

E-commerce websites with different server configurations.

3. Least Connections Algorithm

New request goes to the server with the fewest active connections.

Advantages

Good for long user sessions
Better traffic management
Disadvantages
Slightly complex
Real-Time Example

Banking applications and chat applications.

4. Weighted Least Connections

Combines:

Server weight
Least active connections

Powerful servers handle more traffic.

Real-Time Example

Cloud platforms and enterprise applications.

5. IP Hash Algorithm

Client IP address decides the server.

Formula:
Hash(IP Address) → Server

Same user always connects to same server.

Advantages

Session persistence

Disadvantages
Uneven traffic possible
Real-Time Example

Login-based applications.

6. Least Response Time

Request goes to server with:

Lowest response time
Least active connections
Advantages
Faster performance
Real-Time Example

High-performance APIs and streaming platforms.

7. Random Algorithm

Randomly selects a server.

Advantages
Very simple
Disadvantages
Traffic imbalance possible